article.headline: Air Force 62, Utah 49
article.story: AIR FORCE ACADEMY, Colo. (AP) -- A.J. Kuhle scored 17 points on 5-of-8 shooting Monday to lead Air Force to a 62-49 win over Utah, keeping the Falcons atop the Mountain West Conference. Air Force (14-2, 4-0 MWC) won its 12th consecutive game, while Utah (15-5, 3-2 MWC) lost its second straight conference contest. Air Force won the battle between the nation's top two scoring defenses, forcing 20 turnovers while committing only nine. "Utah is the benchmark which every team in this league measures themselves against. This (win) nationally cements that this is not a fluke," Air Force coach Joe Scott said. After trailing 29-24 at the half, Utah rallied to a 40-38 lead with 10:05 to play on a 3-pointer by Richard Chaney. A layup by Tim Keller (16 points) gave the Falcons the lead back for good with 8:13 left. Two free throws by Chaney pulled the Utes to within three (49-46) with 4:22 left, but a layup by Joel Gerlach on the following possession put Air Force up 51-46. After going 0-for-3 from the field in the first half, Gerhlach responded with six points at critical points in the second half. The Utes outshot the Falcons, 55.3 percent to 51.4 percent, but the Air Force defense prevailed. The Falcons held Utah's Nick Jacobson to 10 points on 4-of-11 shooting. "(Air Force) plays with a unique system, the Princeton system and they have very good shooters and very smart players. I've played against them for 15 years and I always talked about how tough they were," Utah coach Rick Majerus said.
